        "paragraph_index": 3,
        "text": "| Step | Interpretation |\n|---|---|\n| Speciation of oxalic acid | The key transition is **pKa₂ = 3.8**, so the fully deprotonated ligand **oxalate, C₂O₄²⁻**, becomes important at about this pH. |\n| Precipitating species | Calcium oxalate precipitation depends on **free C₂O₄²⁻**, not just total oxalate. |\n| Ca–oxalate interaction | The aqueous Ca–oxalate complex is fairly stable (**log β ≈ 3.2**), so once oxalate appears, calcium binds it readily. |\n| Solid formation | The solid hydrate equilibrium corresponds to a very small solubility product (approximately **10^-7.86** at 25 °C, I = 0.1 M), so precipitation is favored once enough C₂O₄²⁻ is present. |",
